{"cursor":"35234","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox Unit\n| bgcolour = #0000FF name = Metre image = caption = standard = SI base unit\n| quantity = Length symbol = m namedafter = units1 = U.S. customary inunits1 =\n| â 3.2808 ft units2 =   inunits2 = â 39.370 in\n}} The 'metre' ('meter' in American English), symbol 'm', is the fundamental\nunit of length in the International System of Units (SI). {{cite web\n|url=http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Units/meter.html |title=Base unit definitions:\nMeter |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology |accessdate=2010-09-\n28 }} Originally intended to be one ten-millionth of the distance from the\nEarth's equator to the North Pole (at sea level), its definition has been\nperiodically refined to reflect growing knowledge of metrology. Since 1983, it\nhas been defined as \"the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during\na time interval of 1/299,792,458 of a second.\"\n","linknr":692,"url":"Metre","recorded":1362544490,"links":172,"instances":["length","physics","unit","colour","geography","french_revolution"],"pdf":["http://arxiv.org/pdf/physics/0412078.pdf","http://www.bipm.org/utils/common/pdf/mep/M-e-P_I2_633.pdf","http://www.bipm.org/utils/common/pdf/mep/M-e-P_I2_633.pdf","http://www.nist.gov/calibrations/upload/4998.pdf","http://www.nist.gov/calibrations/upload/4998.pdf","http://www.ngs.noaa.gov/PUBS_LIB/FedRegister/FRdoc59-5442.pdf","http://ts.nist.gov/MeasurementServices/Calibrations/upload/4998.pdf","http://www1.bipm.org/utils/common/pdf/si_brochure_8.pdf","http://www1.bipm.org/utils/common/pdf/si_brochure_8.pdf","http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Constants/codata.pdf","http://www.metricationmatters.com/docs/Spelling_metre_or_meter.pdf","http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP330/sp330.pdf","http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/pdf/sp811.pdf","http://ts.nist.gov/WeightsAndMeasures/Metric/upload/FRN_Vol_73_No_96_16May2008_SI_Interpretation.pdf","http://www.metricationmatters.com/docs/Wilk